         <div type="translation">
            <p>To the Divine [Spirits] of Valeria Flo[ren]tina, deare[st] daught[er], 
                      who lived for three years, [X months(?)] Lucius Valerius Valer[ianus] 
                      and Concordia [---], (her) parents, made (this) for (her), well-deserving.</p>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>The letters are deeply but crudely carved, without shading. Horizontal lines of ordination 
                       are visible between lines. "A"s are carved with the crossbar descending diagonally from the second 
                       stroke in lines 2, 3 and 5 and with crossbars absent in lines 7, 8, and 9.</p>
            <p>Line 5: The number of months the deceased lived is likely missing.</p>
            <p>Line 8: It is uncertain whether there is anything missing after “Concordia” as Concordia is a cognomen and tends to appear by itself or after the gentilicium, but there may have been an inversion of the usual ordering of names, in which case Concordia’s gentilicium is missing. A title indicating Concordia’s relationship to the deceased, e.g. “mater,” is common in such a position, but “parentes” in line 9 precludes that possibility.</p>
         </div>
